Diagnosis . Recognizable by having pronotal basal angles sharp at apex, usually not denticulate (occasionally very small denticle present); elytra punctate and pubescent (glabrous in specimens from Japan ) only on lateral intervals, with microsculpture on elytral disc in baso-medial portion consisting of more or less isodiametric meshes and usually with one to four preapical setigerous pores in interval 7 ; metepisterna less than 1.3 times as long as wide; protibia usually with two ventroapical spines in transverse row; and apical spur of protibia not dentate at margins. The internal sac of the median lobe of aedeagus (
Figs 32–33
) is with a large longitudinal spiny patch along the left side. Body length 9.4–14.6 mm .

The species is also known from the southern Russian Far East (Amur Province, Khabarovsk and Maritime Territories, southern Kurils), North and South Korea including Jejudo, and Japan (Hokkaido, Honshu, Shikoku, Kyushu, and Ryukyu Islands) (
Habu 1973
;
Lafer 1989
;
Kryzhanovskij et al . 1995
;
Kataev 1997
;
Kataev et al . 2003
; Moon &
Paik 2006
).
